geographic coordinate data and routing information to calculate dynamic lead 
times.More importantly, the integration of wholesale inventory levels serves as 
a foundational predictive signal for retail sales. A common failure in naive 
retail forecasting is equating historical sales data directly with historical 
consumer demand. In reality, historical sales represent constrained demand. If 
a MENY supermarket experiences a stockout of a highly demanded fresh produce 
item due to a logistical delay from an ASKO warehouse, the recorded sales for 
that day artificially truncate the true demand curve.To achieve optimal results 
in the competition, the strategy must include a rigorous algorithmic adjustment 
for censorship mitigation. If a dataset reveals zero sales for an item that 
historically moves high volumes, a secondary classification model must be 
trained to predict the probability of a supply-side stockout. If a stockout is 
deemed highly probable, the zero-sales entry should be treated as a missing 
value (NaN) during the training phase, or imputed using 
expectation-maximization techniques. This prevents the primary regression model 
from learning artificially suppressed demand curves, thereby maintaining the 
integrity of the forecasting architecture.Advanced Feature Engineering: 
Temporal and Macroeconomic DimensionsIn strictly time-boxed predictive 
competitions such as the NM i AI 2026 championship, the sophistication of the 
feature engineering pipeline universally supersedes the raw mathematical 
complexity of the underlying predictive algorithm. The NorgesGruppen dataset, 
likely structured around millions of interactions between individual stores, 
specific SKUs, and temporal timestamps, requires immediate transformation from 
normalized relational architectures into a dense, stationary feature matrix 
suitable for gradient boosting or neural network ingestion.The foundation of 
any retail forecasting model lies in its temporal topologies. However, 
simplistic lag variables are entirely insufficient for capturing the noise 
inherent in daily point-of-sale data. The strategic approach must deploy an 
expansive and robust array of rolling statistics and autoregressive mechanisms. 
Target lags should incorporate historical sales at standard intervals—such as 
$t-1, t-2, \dots, t-7, t-14$, and $t-28$—to capture immediate momentum and 
strict weekly seasonality. Beyond basic lags, the pipeline must compute rolling 
window aggregations, calculating the mean, median, standard deviation, and 
skewness of sales over 7-day, 14-day, 30-day, and 60-day operational 
windows.The standard deviation metric serves as a vital proxy for demand 
volatility, allowing the algorithm to mathematically distinguish between staple 
goods with uniform, highly predictable demand (e.g., standard dairy products) 
and highly sporadic specialty items that exhibit bursty purchasing patterns. 
Furthermore, Exponential Moving Averages (EMA) must be implemented to provide 
greater mathematical weight to recent observations, capturing abrupt shifts in 
consumer behavior triggered by sudden price adjustments or viral social media 
trends.Beyond internal autoregressive features, the superiority of machine 
learning in contemporary demand planning stems from its capacity to ingest 
exogenous, forward-looking signals. Relying solely on historical data forces 
planning into a continual reaction mode, firefighting exceptions rather than 
driving proactive strategy.Meteorological covariates represent a critical 
external signal. Weather fluctuations dictate immediate and severe retail 
shifts; therefore, temperature deviations, precipitation forecasts, and extreme 
weather event probabilities must be mapped to regional store coordinates. A 
sudden, unexpected drop in temperature dynamically accelerates consumer demand 
for root vegetables and heating supplies while simultaneously cannibalizing the 
sales of cold beverages and seasonal summer items.The feature space must also 
rigorously model the mechanics of retail promotions. Promotions, advertising 
campaigns, and trade events are vital components of marketing strategy, but 
accurately measuring their impact requires advanced feature representation. The 
matrix must denote not merely a binary indicator of a promotion, but the 
precise mathematical depth of the discount relative to the 30-day historical 
average price. Advanced models must further calculate cross-price elasticity to 
identify cannibalization and halo effects. If a premium coffee brand is heavily 
discounted, it will likely cannibalize the sales of adjacent standard brands on 
the same shelf. Identifying these interactive clusters via correlation matrices 
and embedding them as features is essential for accurate aggregate forecasting 
across the entire retail network.Feature CategorySpecific Engineered 
