Statistical TaggingWhile tabular sales data and structured metadata form the 
core of the predictive matrix, modern retail datasets frequently encompass vast 
amounts of unstructured text. This includes complex product descriptions, 
hierarchical category definitions, promotional campaign text, and potentially 
even granular receipt line items. To extract maximal predictive value from the 
NorgesGruppen dataset within the strict 69-hour competition window, teams must 
rapidly parse and categorize this unstructured text to generate distinct 
categorical features.Given the constraints on computational overhead and 
training time, deploying massive Large Language Models (LLMs) for text feature 
extraction during the competition is strategically suboptimal. The latency in 
inference and the complexity of fine-tuning violate the necessity for rapid 
iteration. Instead, state-of-the-art strategy dictates the use of highly 
optimized, statistical part-of-speech taggers and sequence labelers, such as 
those based on second-order Markov models, exemplified by the Trigrams'n'Tags 
(TnT) architecture.The underlying mathematical framework of models like TnT 
relies on transition probabilities between tag pairs and output probabilities 
based on recent categories, operating smoothly across large corpora. When 
applied to retail product descriptions, this methodology allows for the rapid 
identification of key nouns, brand modifiers, and descriptive adjectives, which 
can then be clustered into structured categorical variables.A significant 
challenge in processing retail text is the high prevalence of "unknown 
words"—novel brand names, unique product identifiers, or localized Norwegian 
slang that do not exist in standard training lexicons. The strategic advantage 
of statistical tagging architectures like TnT is their robust handling of 
unknown words through suffix analysis. By analyzing suffixes up to 10 
characters long and utilizing restricted trie-based analysis for infrequent 
words, the model can accurately categorize novel product names without 
requiring extensive retraining.Furthermore, the implementation of beam search 
algorithms within these tagging processes drastically optimizes processing 
speed. By employing an optimized Viterbi algorithm with a specific threshold 
(e.g., theta = 1000), the tagging speed can be doubled while maintaining high 
accuracy, achieving processing rates between 30,000 and 60,000 tokens per 
second. This extreme computational efficiency is critical during the 69-hour 
competition, allowing teams to instantly re-process text features whenever the 
core dataset is updated or expanded.The output of this statistical tagging 
process transforms chaotic product descriptions into standardized, encoded 
columns (e.g., extracting the core item type, the packaging format, and the 
flavor profile from a single messy string). These refined categorical features 
are then passed directly into the primary predictive models, providing a 
